04719nam a22005415i 9780520940567DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20072007cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209405677 a10.1525/97805209405672doi  a(DE-B1597)518826  a(OCoLC)609849952  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aJC574.2.U6bL535 2007eb 7aHIS0360002bisacsh04a320.51/3097322200aLiberalism for a New Century /cKevin Mattson, Neil Jumonville. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2007] 4cÂ©2007  a1 online resource (270 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tIntroduction: Liberalism, Past And Future Tense -- t1. The Liberal Spirit In America And Its Paradoxes -- t2. The Contemporary Critique Of The Enlightenment: Its Irrelevance To America And Liberalism -- t3. Liberalism And The Conservative Imagination -- t4 Liberalism And Belief -- t5. Liberal Tolerance At Middle Age -- t6. Liberalism And Democracy: A Troubled Marriage -- t7. What Liberals Owe To Radicals -- t8. Liberalism, Science, And The Future Of Evolution -- t9. Liberalism And Family Values -- t10. Liberalism And Religion -- t11. Liberalism, Environmentalism, And The Promise Of National Greatness -- t12. Liberalism, Internationalism, And Iran Today -- t13. Beyond Iraq: Toward A New Liberal Internationalism -- tNotes -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAmerican liberalism today is in a state of confusion and disarray, with the "L word" widely considered a term of derision. By examining both the historical past and the fractious present, Liberalism for a New Century restores a proud political tradition and carves out a formidable defense of its philosophical tenets. This manifesto for a New Liberalism issues an urgent and cogent call for the most important rethinking of its values since the late 1960s, when conservatives reenergized themselves after Barry Goldwater's infamous loss. The essays in this volume, most of them never before published, are written by a leading group of historians, journalists, and public intellectuals. Some of the nation's most highly respected liberal minds explore such topics as the classical liberal tradition, postmodernism's challenge to the American "Enlightenment," the civil rights era, the influence of twentieth-century radicals on American liberalism, the 1950s, tolerance, the cold war, and whether liberalism should have a large and aggressive vision. One essay considers liberalism in Iran and what American liberals might learn from this movement. Fast-paced and encompassing such hot-button issues as the family and religion, here are ringside-seat arguments between people who don't often get to engage with one another: right-leaning liberals like Peter Berkowitz and John Patrick Diggins, and leftier liberals like Michael Tomasky and Mona Harrington. The result is a lively and stimulating collection that articulates a clear-minded alternative to the conservative ascendancy in American history and offers a timely and essential contribution to the growing national debate.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aLiberalismxUnited States. 0aLiberalismzUnited States. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh1 aJumonville, Neil, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMattson, Kevin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520940567423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9